    				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						) Infinita[e] Libroru[m] nuga[e]. Omnia vulgaria, pra[e]ter cursum Singularis viri, 
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						aspirantis ad maximam rerum scientia[m],
    						et inco[m]parabile[m] actionem.
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Continu&egrave; Sibi quisq[ue] excitandus. )	
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				) Infinite are the trifles of books. All common things are irrelvant to the path of the Singular man,
    				aspiring to the greatest knowledge of things and to incomparable deeds.
    				Everyone must continuously be stimulated by themselves. ) 
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Solus virum agit, qui ipsa 
    						Artium, professionumq[ue] opera operatur:
    						eademq[ue] in mundo vtilissima.
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				A man acts alone, who devotes his work to just the arts and professions: 
    				though they are most useful in the world.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		
